McNemar Test Conclusions


Extreme First Condition:

No Yes
High 31 52
Low 24 59


\(\chi^2(1) = 10.32, p = 0.001\)

  • There is a significant change in judgement evaluation between the high and low risky doors.

  • The odds of stating the extreme value given they are seeing the high-risk door is 2.17 times that of seeing the low-risk door and not stating the extreme value.

Post-Hoc Pairwise Fisher-Exact Tests

value comparison odds_ratio p_value CI_low CI_upper p_value_adj
High No Extreme : Extreme 1st 0.8396 0.6266 0.4197 1.6728 0.9700
High No Extreme : Extreme Last 1.3226 0.4850 0.6284 2.8166 0.9700
High Extreme 1st : Extreme Last 1.5752 0.2316 0.7601 3.3165 0.9264
Low No Extreme : Extreme 1st 0.3095 0.0060 0.1171 0.7541 0.0359
Low No Extreme : Extreme Last 0.5790 0.2573 0.2032 1.5807 0.9264
Low Extreme 1st : Extreme Last 1.8700 0.1317 0.8239 4.4044 0.6583


  • Recalling the extreme value was found to be dependent on condition (\(p = 0.036\)) only when low value options in the No Extreme and Extreme First conditions are considered (Row 4 in the table). Everything else fails to reach significance.


Note:

  • In the contingency tables, Yes indicates the extreme value was recalled, No indicates that it was not.

  • Only recalled outcomes that matched the programmed values were included. i.e., if they saw the High Value Risky Door, 80 was logged as Yes and 60 was logged as No. If they saw the Low Value Risky Door, 20 was logged as Yes, 40 was logged as No. Participants who responded with any other values were removed from the analysis. Only Risky doors were evaluated.

  • In total, removing other responses resulted 135 participants being excluded from these analyses leaving a final N = 237.

  • \(\varphi_c\) is Cramrs V, a measure of association for two nominal variables (i.e., an effect size of sorts). It can take a value between 0 and 1, with 0 indicating no association (i.e., full independence).

  • Post-hoc analysis on each \(\chi^2\) test was conducted by evaluating the standardized residuals from the chi-square analysis because it seemed the most intuitive approach. However, pairwise Pearson Chi-squared or Fisher Exact tests across the three conditions were also run. The p_value_adj column shows corrected p-values using the Holm-Bonferroni method.
